The paper deals with a distributed binary hypothesis testing problem involving communication over a noisy channel, which is a classic problem in information theory (cs.IT). The paper also considers privacy constraints, which is a topic in computer security (cs.CR). The use of a discrete memoryless source and the consideration of average distortion as a measure of privacy suggest that the paper may also be relevant to multimedia applications (cs.MM) and signal processing (cs.SI). Finally, the paper uses information-theoretic tools to study the trade-offs between different performance metrics, which is a topic in machine learning (cs.LG).
